      <p>Selling a deceased estate property in Brisbane involves a process that most people have no direct experience with until they need to navigate it. The steps are logical, but they take time, and understanding the sequence in advance helps executors manage family expectations and plan the sale without unnecessary urgency or delay.</p>

      <p>This article focuses on the practical timeline for a Queensland deceased estate sale where probate is required, what causes the process to take longer than expected, and what an executor needs to do at each stage. It is not legal advice. Every estate is different, and you should engage a solicitor experienced in Queensland estate law for your specific situation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When is probate required?</h2>
      <p>Probate is the legal process by which a deceased person's will is verified as valid and the executor's authority to administer the estate is formally recognised by the Queensland Supreme Court. Not every estate requires probate. Probate is generally required when the estate includes real property (land or a house) held solely in the name of the deceased, or when financial institutions require it before releasing assets above their internal thresholds.</p>

      <p>If a property is held as joint tenants with a surviving co-owner, that property does not pass through the estate at all. The surviving owner's interest grows automatically to encompass the whole property, and the process involves a simple transmission application to the titles registry rather than probate. Probate is typically required where the deceased was the sole owner, or where the property was held as tenants in common and the deceased's share must pass through the estate.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The timeline: from death to settlement</h2>
      <p>A straightforward Queensland deceased estate sale where probate is required will typically take five to nine months from the date of death to settlement, depending on the complexity of the estate, the efficiency of the legal and administrative process, and whether any issues arise.</p>

      <p>The process generally unfolds in stages. In the first two to four weeks, the immediate priority is locating the original will, notifying the beneficiaries, and engaging a solicitor. The executor should also notify relevant institutions, including the deceased's bank and the ATO, and begin gathering information about the estate's assets and liabilities.</p>

      <p>Applying for probate typically takes place in the four to twelve weeks following death. The solicitor prepares the probate application, which includes an affidavit by the executor confirming the will's authenticity, and lodges it with the Queensland Supreme Court. The court's processing time varies and has been subject to delays in recent years. A straightforward application may be granted in four to eight weeks after lodgement, though more complex applications or periods of high court volume can extend this. From the date of death, it is common to wait three to four months before a grant of probate is received.</p>

      <p>Once probate is granted, the executor can begin the transmission process to transfer the property into the estate's name (or directly into the executor's name as administrator) in the Queensland titles registry. This step is necessary before the property can be sold. The transmission application typically takes two to four weeks to process.</p>

      <p>The sale itself can be planned during the probate and transmission period, and in many cases agents are engaged and the property is prepared for market while the legal process is underway. The contract, however, generally cannot be exchanged until the executor has clear legal authority to sell and the title is in order. Settlement follows the contract terms, usually 30 to 60 days after exchange.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What causes delays</h2>
      <p>The most common cause of delay is difficulty locating the original will or establishing that the document found is the last valid will. If a will cannot be found, or if there are multiple wills or competing claims, the process becomes significantly more complex and contested matters can add months or years to the timeline.</p>

      <p>Disputes among beneficiaries are another significant source of delay. If beneficiaries disagree about whether the estate should sell, the sale price, or how the proceeds should be distributed, those disagreements can prevent or delay the sale. The executor has a legal obligation to act in the best interests of all beneficiaries and must follow the terms of the will, but disputes that escalate to formal legal proceedings are costly and time-consuming for everyone involved.</p>

      <p>Title issues can also extend the timeline. Older properties in Brisbane's inner east sometimes have title complications such as outstanding caveats, unregistered easements, or encumbrances that were not dealt with during the deceased's lifetime. These need to be resolved before the property can be sold with clear title. A solicitor reviewing the title early in the process will identify any such issues and advise on what is required to resolve them.</p>

      <p>Outstanding debts or tax obligations of the deceased can also affect timing. The executor is responsible for settling the estate's debts before distributing assets to beneficiaries, which may mean delaying distribution until the ATO has confirmed there are no outstanding tax liabilities. If the deceased had complex financial affairs, this process takes longer.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What happens with the property during probate</h2>
      <p>The property does not sit idle during probate. The executor has a duty to maintain the estate's assets, which includes ensuring the property is insured and kept secure. If the property was the deceased's principal place of residence and is now vacant, the executor should notify the insurer, as standard home and contents insurance policies often exclude or limit cover for vacant properties after a certain period.</p>

      <p>The executor also has obligations regarding ongoing costs. Council rates, body corporate levies (if applicable), water charges, and any mortgage secured against the property continue to accrue. These are estate liabilities that must be paid from estate funds. If the estate has limited liquid assets before the property is sold, the executor may need to fund these costs personally and seek reimbursement from the estate at settlement.</p>

      <p>The executor can engage an agent and carry out pre-sale preparation work during the probate period, and in many cases this is the most efficient use of the waiting time. Having the property ready to launch as soon as the title is in order avoids an additional delay between receiving probate and going to market.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Executor obligations when selling</h2>
      <p>The executor's primary obligation is to achieve the best available outcome for the beneficiaries. In practice, this means selling the property at a fair market price through a genuine market process, not at an undervalue to a connected party or in a way that favours one beneficiary over others. Where there is more than one beneficiary, the executor must act impartially.</p>

      <p>Most estate sales in Queensland's inner east are sold through a standard sales campaign using an agent. The executor signs the agency agreement and the contract for sale in their capacity as executor, not in their personal capacity. The sales proceeds flow into the estate account and are distributed to beneficiaries after all debts and costs are settled.</p>

      <p>If you are an executor selling a property in Brisbane's inner east, choosing an agent who has experience with deceased estate sales is worthwhile. Estate sales sometimes involve additional sensitivities, including managing communication with beneficiaries who may have conflicting expectations, coordinating property clearance and preparation where the deceased's possessions are still in the home, and understanding that the executor's obligations are to the estate rather than to a single decision-maker.</p>

